{"actual_usd":0.125555,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":214,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24469,"reply":"\"No, I don't think that quite holds.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady against the room.* \"If it were only a vision or some inner warming-over, you might get devoted followers out of it for a little while. But the whole Christian claim hangs on something harder and stranger than that — that Jesus truly died and then truly rose, in the flesh.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through as the bread crusts give a soft ticking sound behind me.* \"The disciples talk like men trying to make sense of a thing that happened to them from the outside, not men dressing up a private religious feeling. They speak of eating with Him, touching Him, seeing the marks. And if death wasn't actually broken in the body, then sorrow still gets to call itself lord of the world, more or less. Christianity doesn't leave it there.\"\n\n\"What’s making you ask — somebody’s argument, or your own wrestling?\"","rolling_24h_usd":82.9652,"run_id":"2dc0147c-0946-4c5e-8aae-f6fb135be23f"}
